           	<td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000">
                      <font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> OK I may have started my first necro in December (making me a relative newbie to many of you) and even though I read and play a lot I'm still learning quite a bit.<br /><br />I understand charmed pets will steal up to 1/3 of the experience from a kill depending on how much damage we deal to said mob...and, charming in ME, I finally discovered just how much a hasted, charmed pet can do against a slowed undead mob...I had skeletal drudges going through slowed vamps and losing no more than 5% of their health...whereas an unslowed vamp would easily take said pet down to 60% health if not lower...<br /><br />So here's my thought...and maybe this should go in the developer's forum or maybe you'll all decide it should fade away as a low priority since the effect is so great, but since shackle of spirit (and other slow spells) has such a huge effect on the mobs power as well as your level on its hate list, shouldn't spells like this be taken into account and increase the amount of experience we get vs our pet from said mob?  After all, Shackle of Spirit and Augmentation of Death do A LOT more "damage" to the mob then any DoT I can cast on him...only it's indirect and, therefore, doesn't count if I understand "the rules" correctly...not much different a line of thinking as saying a cleric doesn't deserve to share the experience when grouped with a warrior she keeps alive...quite irrational IMO...</span id="msg"></font>
           	</td>
                    </tr>
